<subSubSection id="FBCD3A95318A75AADEDE694B5CAFBAAC" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="differential diagnosis">
<paragraph id="390765F0FBABDFD06BF8D3013D17BA33" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Differential diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="75C37721822230AEEB7A8A8C46DEAD16" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="35554F4F7D59185C8D553F40D41A02FB" authorityName="d'Orchymont" authorityYear="1943" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Helopeltarium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Helopeltarium" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="48A47F4B4D204A500EAF81FD69C4F1F2" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Helopeltarium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a very unique appearance within acidocerines. The flattened and broadly explanate body shape and concealed labrum, accompanied by smooth surface, short and stout maxillary palps, lacking elytral serial punctures is unique in the subfamily. It may appear like a very small 
<taxonomicName id="80229E34AB9738F4C809BBE4730CE2F7" authorityName="Bergroth" authorityYear="1888" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Helobata" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Helobata" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="23D610CA87CFFF1A43E06DAAB1CB1B2B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Helobata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but besides geographic origin, the lack of serial punctures, smooth surface and short maxillary palps sets 
<taxonomicName id="FE0EB5134B91DE8197AE2FF2137F9C6F" authorityName="d'Orchymont" authorityYear="1943" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Helopeltarium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Helopeltarium" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="0FFDD56E1779CC61555D7473F813C9CF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Helopeltarium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
apart very easily. The configuration of the aedeagus in 
<taxonomicName id="7E3998284AA83BC91E12F06F27489B35" authorityName="d'Orchymont" authorityYear="1943" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Helopeltarium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Helopeltarium" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="01C35A6862F2BB340EC6E4E6696EE034" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Helopeltarium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is very similar to that of some 
<taxonomicName id="2D974368A2DC36916833C08925DA5BC8" authorityName="Mulsant" authorityYear="1844" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Helochares" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Helochares" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="643608495843E03C9510ECF48F0AC317" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Helochares</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the external morphology alone allows for its immediate recognition.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A906F4D4B2B7066A6841681E282AA89F" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="FAA2CE4CD5C4412549F136111155AA1B" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E2151C6FDFD2410D16D2D93D21BEED2F" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="EECFE17CAF9C430C57D009FB9412C739" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Indo-Malayan</emphasis>
: Myanmar (formerly Burma); Fig. 
